<section class="card">
  <h2>About Lettuce</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Cool-season greens—fast maturity, limited by heat more than frost.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Lettuce prefers cool conditions and tolerates light frost.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), lettuce is rarely limited by first frost. Instead, viability is determined by how well you fit maturity into cool windows before heat stress triggers bolting.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, lettuce is often one of the most reliable crops because it matures quickly and tolerates cool soil. The main constraint is summer heat, not frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 4–6 weeks before to 2 weeks after last frost</li>
    <li><strong>Indoor start (optional):</strong> 4–6 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 30–60 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light (brief dips near 32°F / 0°C usually tolerated)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline planning ranges. Heat spikes reduce quality and shorten harvest window.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 55–70°F (13–21°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~40°F (4°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Bolting risk:</strong> Above ~75–80°F (24–27°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Lettuce tolerates light frost, but repeated hard freezes can damage leaves. In most climates, lettuce fails from heat before it fails from frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For context on frost types, see:
    <a href="/guides/light-freeze-vs-hard-freeze/">Light freeze vs hard freeze</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring vs Fall Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Lettuce fits two reliable windows in many climates:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring crop:</strong> Sow early so harvest finishes before sustained heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall crop:</strong> Count backward from first frost, allowing buffer for slower late-season growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a> to anchor fall sowing from your frost boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~400–700 GDD (base 50), depending on variety and harvest stage</p>

  <p>
    Lettuce has a modest heat requirement. In cool summers, maturity may drift slightly beyond label timing, but overall GDD demand is low compared to warm-season crops.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    To understand how frost windows and seasonal heat interact, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most lettuce varieties reach harvest in <strong>30–60 frost-free days</strong>.
    Because lettuce tolerates light frost, the effective window often extends beyond first frost in mild conditions.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (very reliable)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Rarely; quick maturity reduces risk</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Sometimes helpful in fall (light cover to extend harvest)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Lettuce tolerates light frost near 32°F (0°C), though quality can decline with repeated freezing.
    For modeling consistency, treat 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary, but understand that lettuce often survives brief dips.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select bolt-resistant varieties for spring plantings</li>
    <li>Sow early to maximize cool-season runway</li>
    <li>For fall crops, add buffer for slower late-season growth</li>
    <li>Use partial shade in hot climates to reduce bolting risk</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, lettuce is viable in nearly all short seasons because of its modest heat requirement and frost tolerance.
    The main constraint is fitting maturity into cool weeks before sustained heat, not surviving first frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can lettuce survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Light frost near 32°F (0°C) is often tolerated, though repeated freezing may damage leaves.
  </p>

  <h3>Why did my lettuce bolt?</h3>
  <p>
    Bolting is usually triggered by sustained heat, long days, or plant stress—not frost.
  </p>

  <h3>Is lettuce good for very short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Its quick maturity and low GDD requirement make it one of the safest options.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Lettuce is limited more by heat than frost.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 30–60 days, ~400–700 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>